%N A395392 Decimal expansion of the surface area of the solid of revolution formed by rotating a unit half-width lemniscate of Bernoulli about the horizontal axis.
%C A395392 The lemniscate of Bernoulli can be described by (x^2 + y^2)^2 = a^2*(x^2 - y^2) in Cartesian coordinates, or r^2 = a^2*cos(2*phi) in polar coordinates, where a is the half-width. Here we take a = 1.
%D A395392 J. Dennis Lawrence, A Catalog of Special Plane Curves, Dover Publications Inc., New York, 1972, p. 122.
%D A395392 Babu Ram, Engineering Mathematics, Pearson, 2009. See example 8.26.
%H A395392 G. N. Berman, <a href="https://archive.org/details/g.-n.-berman-a-problem-book-in-mathematical-analysis-mir-1980/page/177/mode/1up">A Problem Book in Mathematical Analysis</a>, 2nd ed., Mir Publishers, Moscow, 1980, p. 177, Problem 2607 (solution on page 397).
%H A395392 Mandeep Beniwal, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lLtiv3iSjVE">Surface of solid of revolution of Lemniscate</a>, Smart study helper, YouTube video, 2021.
%H A395392 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A395392/a395392.png">Illustration of the solid of revolution</a>.
